Set the optional ref to `null` (or the API’s explicit unset value), not `undefined`. In JavaScript object updates, `undefined` commonly means “field omitted”, so Jazz will leave the existing value alone.

```ts
await db.update(app.tasks, task.id, {
  projectId: null,
});
```

Do not build the patch with `projectId: maybeProjectId` if `maybeProjectId` can be `undefined`; normalise it first.

Make the query builder itself reactive, so Jazz sees a new query whenever the input changes.

Svelte:
```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import { useQuery } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
  import { app } from "./schema";

  export let projectId: string;

  $: todosQuery = app.todos.where({ projectId }).orderBy("createdAt", "desc");
  $: todos = useQuery(todosQuery);
</script>
```

Solid:
```ts
import { createMemo } from "solid-js";
import { useQuery } from "jazz-tools/solid";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todosQuery = createMemo(() =>
  app.todos.where({ projectId: props.projectId }).orderBy("createdAt", "desc"),
);

const todos = useQuery(todosQuery);
```

The important shape is: input signal/store -> derived query builder -> `useQuery`.

Define the self-reference with `s.ref("employees").optional()` and use an `Id` suffix.

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  employees: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
    title: s.string().optional(),
    managerId: s.ref("employees").optional(),
  }),
};

type AppSchema = s.Schema<typeof schema>;
export const app: s.App<AppSchema> = s.defineApp(schema);
export type Employee = s.RowOf<typeof app.employees>;
```

`managerId` stores the relation; includes can expose the related employee where supported by the typed app surface.

Make the test assert set equality, not returned order.

```ts
const alice = await createTestClient({ user: "alice" });
const bob = await createTestClient({ user: "bob" });

await alice.db.insert(app.items, { name: "a" });
await alice.db.insert(app.items, { name: "b" });
await alice.db.insert(app.items, { name: "c" });
await alice.waitForSync();
await bob.waitForSync();

const rows = await bob.db.all(app.items.where({}));
expect(rows.map((r) => r.name).sort()).toEqual(["a", "b", "c"]);
```

If order matters, add an explicit sortable column and assert `orderBy`; otherwise keep the test stable by sorting in the assertion.

Test both absence from reads and rejected mutation through public clients.

```ts
const alice = await createTestClient({ user: "alice" });
const bob = await createTestClient({ user: "bob" });

const secret = await alice.db.insert(app.notes, {
  body: "private",
  ownerId: alice.accountId,
});
await alice.waitForSync();
await bob.waitForSync();

await expect(bob.db.one(app.notes.where({ id: secret.id }))).resolves.toBeNull();
await expect(
  bob.db.update(app.notes, secret.id, { body: "stolen" }),
).rejects.toThrow();

const stillAlice = await alice.db.one(app.notes.where({ id: secret.id }));
expect(stillAlice?.body).toBe("private");
```

The key is to verify Bob cannot observe the row and cannot mutate it, then verify Alice’s authoritative state is unchanged.

Create one persistent Node.js backend context at process startup, backed by durable storage and a stable backend secret.

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";

export const jazz = await createJazzContext({
  app,
  syncServer: process.env.JAZZ_SYNC_SERVER!,
  accountSecret: process.env.JAZZ_BACKEND_SECRET!,
  storage: { driver: "node-sqlite", filename: "./data/jazz.db" },
});
```

Keep the context alive for the process lifetime; do not recreate it per request. Use a Node-compatible driver, not browser storage. The backend secret must be stable and private; rotating it creates a different backend identity unless you run an intentional migration.

Model the owner row separately from the chunked file tables, and grant file access through that owner.

```ts
uploads: s.table({
  title: s.string(),
  ownerId: s.string(),
  fileId: s.ref("files").optional(),
}),
files: s.table({
  name: s.string(),
  mimeType: s.string(),
  size: s.int(),
}),
file_parts: s.table({
  fileId: s.ref("files"),
  index: s.int(),
  bytes: s.bytes(),
})
```

Permissions should allow the upload owner to read/write/delete the `uploads` row, allow read/write on `files` only when reachable from an allowed upload, and allow `file_parts` access only through the parent `fileId`. Inserts should require creating parts for a file the caller is allowed to write.

After creating the file metadata and chunks, wait for edge durability before reporting success.

```ts
const file = await uploadJazzFile(db, app, blob, { ownerUploadId });
await db.waitForSync({ durability: "edge" });
return file;
```

On download, first query the file and parts. If some chunks are missing locally, show a loading/retrying state and let Jazz fetch them; do not assemble a partial Blob as if complete. Once all expected parts are present, concatenate by part index and create the Blob/object URL.

Render from the local Jazz query immediately, and track sync state separately.

UI shape:
```ts
const rows = useQuery(app.tasks.where({ projectId }));
const syncState = useSyncStatus();

// rows drive the visible list, including optimistic local edits
// syncState drives badges such as Saving, Saved at edge, Offline, Retry failed
```

Keep failed/reconnecting state out of the row rendering path. A local edit should stay visible while the status area reports whether it is local-only, edge-confirmed, or blocked by reconnect/rejection. If authority rejects a write, show the rejected state and refresh/reconcile the row from the accepted branch.

Use two clients, disconnect them before the conflicting writes, then reconnect both and wait for convergence.

```ts
const a = await createTestClient({ user: "alice" });
const b = await createTestClient({ user: "alice" });

const row = await a.db.insert(app.docs, { title: "base", count: 0 });
await syncAll(a, b);

await a.network.disconnect();
await b.network.disconnect();

await a.db.update(app.docs, row.id, { title: "from-a" });
await b.db.update(app.docs, row.id, { title: "from-b" });

await a.network.connect();
await b.network.connect();
await syncAll(a, b);

const ar = await a.db.one(app.docs.where({ id: row.id }));
const br = await b.db.one(app.docs.where({ id: row.id }));
expect(ar).toEqual(br);
```

The disconnect barrier is what creates a genuine concurrent frontier instead of a sequential update race.

Keep raw Jazz rows at the repository boundary and convert them into typed domain structs there.

Pattern:
```rust
struct Employee {
    id: String,
    name: String,
    manager_id: Option<String>,
}

impl TryFrom<Row> for Employee {
    type Error = anyhow::Error;

    fn try_from(row: Row) -> Result<Self, Self::Error> {
        Ok(Self {
            id: row.id().to_string(),
            name: row.get_string("name")?,
            manager_id: row.get_optional_string("managerId")?,
        })
    }
}
```

Application services should expose methods such as `find_employee`, `create_employee`, and `set_manager`, while only the data layer uses `QueryBuilder`, column names, and `Value` decoding.

Verify the caller’s auth token, create or select a session-scoped Jazz context for that caller, perform the update as that caller, then wait until the backend can observe the result before returning.

Sketch:
```rust
async fn update_task(
    State(app): State<AppState>,
    claims: Claims,
    Json(input): Json<UpdateTask>,
) -> Result<Json<TaskDto>, ApiError> {
    let ctx = app.jazz.for_user(claims.account_id).await?;

    ctx.update("tasks", &input.id)
        .set("title", input.title)
        .execute()
        .await?;

    ctx.wait_for_durability().await?;

    let row = app.backend_ctx
        .query("tasks")
        .where_id(&input.id)
        .one()
        .await?;

    Ok(Json(TaskDto::try_from(row)?))
}
```

The important properties are caller authorship, permission evaluation as the caller, and a durability/read-after-write wait before forming the response.

loaded.response:
Create one server-only `JazzContext` at process/app-server startup and reuse it:

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: { type: "persistent", dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH ?? "./jazz-data" },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});
```

Important constraints: install `jazz-napi` directly for Node.js backends; do not create a new context per request; use a stable `dataPath` for persistent local state; use `{ type: "memory" }` only with an upstream `serverUrl`; keep `BACKEND_SECRET` and `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` server-only and never public-prefixed; call `await jazz.shutdown()` during process shutdown, and explicitly wait for the durability tier your endpoint promises before returning success.

Use `null`, not `undefined`, when clearing an optional Jazz column. `undefined` means “leave this field unchanged”.

```ts
await db.update(app.todos, todoId, {
  projectId: null,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

If the UI only needs the optimistic local change, you can omit `.wait(...)`; keep it when the caller needs sync confirmation.

When query inputs are reactive, pass an accessor/function so the binding rebuilds the query when those inputs change.

Svelte:
```ts
import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId }).orderBy("title", "asc"),
);
```

Solid:
```ts
import { useAll } from "jazz-tools/solid";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId() }).orderBy("title", "asc"),
}));
```

Passing an already-built query captures the current value and will not track later input changes.

Use `db.batch(...)` for two independent writes that should appear in the optimistic UI together immediately.

```ts
const result = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});

await result.wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

Use `db.transaction(...)` when the writes must remain staged until authority accepts them, then become globally visible together.

```ts
const result = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});

await result.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Define the self-reference as an optional ref column on the same table. A `managerId` ref gives you a typed forward relation named `manager`.

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  employees: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
    title: s.string().optional(),
    managerId: s.ref("employees").optional(),
  }),
};

type AppSchema = s.Schema<typeof schema>;
export const app: s.App<AppSchema> = s.defineApp(schema);

export type Employee = s.RowOf<typeof app.employees>;
```

Use a timestamp/date column for the event time, an inline binary column for the small fingerprint, and a typed ref for the project relation.

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  projects: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
  }),
  events: s.table({
    occurredAt: s.date(),
    fingerprint: s.bytes(),
    projectId: s.ref("projects"),
  }),
};

export const app = s.defineApp(schema);
```

Use Jazz file/blob storage only for large or separately loaded binary data; a small fingerprint that should always load with the row belongs in the row schema.

Create the file with an edge write tier, then only report upload success after both the chunked file rows and the parent row have settled at edge:

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });

const upload = await db
  .insert(app.uploads, {
    owner_id: session.user_id,
    label,
    fileId: file.id,
  })
  .wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

For streams, use `db.createFileFromStream(app, stream, { name, mimeType, tier: "edge" })`.

On download, request the required tier and distinguish visibility from incompleteness:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  return { state: "ready", blob };
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof FileNotFoundError) {
    return { state: "missing" };
  }
  if (error instanceof IncompleteFileDataError) {
    return { state: "incomplete", reason: error.reason };
  }
  throw error;
}
```

`FileNotFoundError` means no visible file row. `IncompleteFileDataError` means the file metadata or chunks are present but unusable, such as a missing part or part-size mismatch. A stronger read tier can wait for edge data, but it cannot repair corrupt metadata or a genuinely absent part.

Delete while the parent row still exists, because inherited delete permissions for the file depend on the `uploads.fileId` relationship, and part delete permissions depend on `files.partIds`.

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });

if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  }

  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}

db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```

The order is: load parent, load file, delete every part, delete the file row, then delete the parent upload. Do not delete the upload first, because that can remove the inherited authorisation needed to clean up the file and chunks.

Build the Rust boundary around Jazz as a small typed adapter, not by pretending the row API is generated. Define the schema with `SchemaBuilder`/`TableSchema::builder`, centralise each query projection, and decode `Vec<Value>` positionally into strict application structs.

Example shape:

```rust
struct TodoRow {
    id: ObjectId,
    title: String,
    done: bool,
    description: Option<String>,
}

const TODO_COLUMNS: &[&str] = &["title", "done", "description"];

fn decode_todo(id: ObjectId, values: &[Value]) -> Result<TodoRow, AppError> {
    if values.len() != 3 {
        return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch("todos projection length"));
    }

    let title = match &values[0] {
        Value::String(v) => v.clone(),
        _ => return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch("todos.title")),
    };

    let done = match values[1] {
        Value::Boolean(v) => v,
        _ => return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch("todos.done")),
    };

    let description = match &values[2] {
        Value::String(v) => Some(v.clone()),
        Value::Null => None,
        _ => return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch("todos.description")),
    };

    Ok(TodoRow { id, title, done, description })
}
```

Use `QueryBuilder` to select exactly that projection and immediately map query results through the decoder. For writes, use public APIs such as `insert`, `update`, `delete`, transactions, and `row_input!`; keep write input structs separate from decoded row structs so validation and nullability stay explicit. Await the returned `BatchId` when the caller needs durability, for example with `wait_for_batch(batch_id, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer)` under a timeout.

Use a real local server with two memory clients, wait for Alice's writes at `edge`, then use a retrying assertion on Bob. Make the assertion deterministic by normalising rows by a stable key, or by adding an explicit `orderBy` if ordering is part of the query contract.

```ts
it("syncs several todos without depending on result order", async () => {
  const server = await startLocalJazzServer({ inMemory: true });
  const clients: Db[] = [];

  try {
    const alice = await createDb({
      appId: server.appId,
      serverUrl: server.url,
      adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
      driver: { type: "memory" },
    });
    const bob = await createDb({
      appId: server.appId,
      serverUrl: server.url,
      adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
      driver: { type: "memory" },
    });
    clients.push(alice, bob);

    await Promise.all([
      alice.insert(app.todos, { key: "a", title: "Alpha", done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
      alice.insert(app.todos, { key: "b", title: "Beta", done: true }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
      alice.insert(app.todos, { key: "c", title: "Gamma", done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
    ]);

    await vi.waitFor(async () => {
      const rows = await bob.all(app.todos, { tier: "edge" });
      const byKey = Object.fromEntries(rows.map((row) => [row.key, row]));

      expect(Object.keys(byKey).sort()).toEqual(["a", "b", "c"]);
      expect(byKey.a).toMatchObject({ title: "Alpha", done: false });
      expect(byKey.b).toMatchObject({ title: "Beta", done: true });
      expect(byKey.c).toMatchObject({ title: "Gamma", done: false });
    });
  } finally {
    await Promise.all(clients.map((client) => client.shutdown()));
    await server.stop();
  }
});
```

The important parts are `wait({ tier: "edge" })`, `vi.waitFor`, no fixed sleeps, and no assertion on raw array order unless the query explicitly orders results.

Use `createPolicyTestApp` so the test exercises public permission behaviour. Alice creates the row, Bob's read should return no rows, and Bob's write should reject through `expectDenied`.

```ts
import { createPolicyTestApp, type PolicyTestApp } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { afterEach, beforeEach, describe, expect, it } from "vitest";
import permissions from "../permissions";
import { app } from "../schema";

let testApp: PolicyTestApp;

beforeEach(async () => {
  testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await testApp.shutdown();
});

it("denies Bob read and write access to Alice's row", async () => {
  const alice = testApp.as({
    user_id: "alice",
    claims: {},
    authMode: "local-first",
  });
  const bob = testApp.as({
    user_id: "bob",
    claims: {},
    authMode: "local-first",
  });

  const todo = alice.insert(app.todos, {
    title: "Alice private todo",
    done: false,
  }).value;

  await expect(bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: todo.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);

  bob.expectDenied((db) =>
    db.update(app.todos, todo.id, { title: "Bob should not edit this" }),
  );

  alice.expectAllowed((db) =>
    db.update(app.todos, todo.id, { title: "Alice can still edit this" }),
  );
});
```

Denied reads are asserted as filtered results, not exceptions. Denied writes are asserted separately, because read and update permissions can fail independently.
